						I am interested in privacy and intellectual property rights as they pertain to user generated content (UGC).
						<p>While users are "credited" for comments, 
						photos, product reviews, etc., corporations are the ones who profit from user contributions, 
						indefinitely. The only compensation is targetted ads and social media affirmation.
						Social networks beg/ask/incentivize users to monitor their platforms for fraud
						by flagging content and bots.
						<P>This kind of benevolent self-contained system 
							worked in the good old days but today things are different,
							 getting worse fast with generative AI and bots.
						</P>
						 <!-- P>Would the network effect be achievable without destruction of IP rights in a liberated system?
						</P -->
						<!-- p>
						 Would social networks differ if users had full and perpetual rights to 
						 control their own data? Today's tangled process is one where companies 
